    <section>
        <h>dependents</h>
        <section id="sbj">
            <h>subject</h>
            <p>Some examples – <ul>
                    <li>older pedagogical examples – <xl id="sbj-older-pedag">
                            <li>
                                <gd>Tha mo mhàthair a’ sgrìobhadh litreach gu m’athair a tha air
                                    falbh. Thubhairt mo mhàthair, “An téid thu do bhocsa nan
                                    litrichean leis an litir seo, Iain?” “Théid,” ars Iain,
                                    “falbhaidh mi an dràsda”. “Fuirich gus an dùin mi i is gus an
                                        <m>cuir mi</m> seòladh oirre. Ceannaich fhéin stamp agus
                                        <m>cuir</m> oirre i.” Tha <m>Iain</m> a’ ruith sìos an
                                    rathad leis an litir ’na làimh. Théid e a steach do oifig a’
                                    phuist, ceannaichidh e stamp is <m>cuiridh e</m> sud air an
                                    litir. [...]</gd>
                                <tr>My mother is writing a letter to my father who is away. My
                                    mother said, “Will you go to the postbox with this letter,
                                    John?” “Yes, I will,” said John, “I will leave now.” “Wait until
                                    I seal it and put an address on it. Buy a stamp and put it on
                                    it.” John is running down the road with the letter in his hand.
                                    He will go into the post office, he will buy a stamp and put
                                    that on the letter. [...]</tr>
                                <ref text="621">td. 5</ref>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <gd>Bha an latha brèagha blàth is thug an athair leis Iain agus Anna
                                    anns a’ chàr. Chaidh iad sìos taobh an locha is stad iad aig
                                    àite bòidheach gorm. <m>Chuir iad</m> an càr a stigh gu taobh an
                                    rathaid is thug iad brat a mach as a’ chàr air son suidhe air.
                                    [...]</gd>
                                <tr>The day was lovely and warm and their father took John and Ann
                                    in the car. They went down the side of the lake and they stopped
                                    at a beautiful green place. They put the car into the side of
                                    the road and they took a blanket out of the car for sitting on.
                                    [...]</tr>
                                <ref text="621">td. 6</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="comps">
            <h>complements</h>
            <p><g>cuir</g> generally takes both an object and a prepositional/adverbial complement – <ul>
                    <li><g>cuir <a href="?gd=air">air</a></g>
                        <en>put something on something</en> – <ul>
                            <li><g>cuir <a href="?gd=seòl">seòladh</a> / <a href="?gd=stampa"
                                        >stampa</a> air <a href="?gd=litir">litir</a></g>
                                <en>put an address/stamp on a letter</en>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><g>cuir <a href="?gd=a-staigh">a-staigh</a></g>
                        <en>put something inside</en></li>
                    <li><g>cuir <a href="?gd=càr">càr</a></g>
                        <en>park/put a car somewhere</en></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>

